commentBody:
@Michael Weilanda

We really get into the weeks with "M" states.  An astonishing 14% of the US states start with M.  Good think Maine has an "E" at the end so we can make ME, because every other letter in Maine is an abbreviation for a different state.

I constantly battle with MS and MI and MO, and MN, before I moved here.

@Michael Weiland

<a href="https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=dLECCmKnrys" target="_blank">https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=dLECCmKnrys</a>

Gary Gulman on how the states got their abbreviations. This clip is from when he did this comedy routine on Conan. Highly recommended!! 🤣🤣

@Francis
Cool observation about Maine. That would make a good clue.
But M's are actually 16%. And M and N together account for 32% of the states.

@Walj

We need an algorithm to give us the logicalest of all the logical things.

Ideas?

@Cal Gal

I always have trouble falling asleep.

But it sounds like your exercise would jazz me up more than calm me down.  "Damn, one more town in South Dakota!"

@Marshall Walthew

Amazing story about your friend's mom.  She sounds like a real Renaissance woman.

I really appreciate people who have a broad respect for competing art forms.  That believe you don't have to hate the Beatles to love Beethoven.

@JayTee
I'm on the same page except for KILLERBEE which seemed a green-paint sort of clue. Aren't killer bees a separate species? Presumably they have the usual bee social organization, including drones who guard the queen, but then so do ordinary honeybees. Am I missing something?

As for the reSMURFacing, points to the constructor for giving us a non-ordinary clue.

@Cat Lady Margaret

Our Cassius manages to get out of his in less than five minutes flat, and I never see him doing it. I was so grateful his most recent surgery did not require the dreaded CONE! 

But one quibble: I'm talking *feline* [post-op wear]! One does not need to be a canine to suffer this indignity. 😹

@Bill in Yokohama

I've never seen an image of the "Gray Lady".  Perhaps she has a DDD bust? 
And perhaps Deb is afraid that if that information became public, she'd lose some of her diginity?

@Vaer
I think all the SMURFs are NYT's version of product placement, what with the movie...

It just seems too frequent to be a coincidence

@Vaer @DW 

The company that runs the two movie theaters here periodically sends me a ballot that allows me to express my interest in movies they're thinking of running here. The Smurfs was probably on one of those, but until DW mentioned it, I'd forgotten it exists.

I thought I had seen a lot of Smurf references in puzzles this week (not just NYT puzzles). I'm glad to know I'm not imagining it.

@Whoa Nellie
SCOTT Farkus, so help me, God!
(If I recalling correctly, he also had a role--like an extra--as one of the classmates, but cleaned up and groomed.)

@Francis

I had veNT before RANT too. 

Hey, if you were a grump, you were a very nice one and didn't even blame the puzzles for your verb tense debacles, no matter how tense you felt about them.

@Francis
I completely relate to your experience solving the puzzle. This one was not an easy for me, possibly because I'd had a maddening, frustrating day and it was carrying over, fragmenting my concentration and making everything harder. I made the same mistakes everyone else did and the puzzle took longer than it should have, but then those heady moments when a section started to click and there's the moment when your brain can grasp what's happening, and the long fills start to reveal where the wrong fills are, and you get the help your need from that.  

Like the creation of Adam, but working a crossword puzzle instead.

@Nora

I just jumped on an inadvertent straight line.  

Any responsibility for poor taste is entirely mine.

@Vaer

You’re welcome. The Michelangelo was easy to picture in my head, but I’ve always liked his stuff. Still haven’t seen any of it in person, though we did see the full-size plaster cast of his David at the Victoria & Albert 20+ years ago. 

After I wrote my review, I saw what Deb had to say about EVOO. That sounded vaguely familiar, but I associate the term with Rachel Ray because I came across it in a different puzzle about a year ago and had no idea what it was.

@Beth in Greenbelt

Great post and thanks for reminding me I need to get out to see a shooting star again.

They are so beautiful but so transient, (I loved your "Where?  Where"?) and it feels like a minor miracle to happen to be looking in the right place at the right time.

@Sam

Try turning the autocheck off sometime. You might find that you know more than you think you do. 

Good luck, and keep having fun!

@Justin

"IMs is not a synonym for DMs"

Citation needed.  ;)

@Jacqui J

That is hilarious!!!!!!!

I would love to see that someday in a NYT puzzle.

@Times Rita

It also appeared in the crossword on 12/27/42, clued as [West Indian cactus].

I *really* don’t want to think about that.

@B
So that's what infuriates you? My Mom's pet peeve is 8 AM in the morning or tonight at 10 PM.
Mine is people who say "I should've went." And I swear I heard "brung" twice this week, as in "she should've brung her a-game." These are sports people on TV.

@Ms. Billie M. Spaight and @Mark Smith

Yes!!  We lived in ARkansas for 18 years, and no end of people (such as hotel check-in staff) would ask, "Long way from Arizona, aren't you?" 
And then there was the mail addressed to AK...(thank goodness for zip codes)...

@Linda Jo

I’m waiting for SMURF to be clued as someone who purchases pseudoephedrine for a person cooking methamphetamine. 

<a href="https://www.weau.com/content/misc/Smurfing-how-meth-users-are-taking-advantage-of-over-the-counter-drugs-490238691.html" target="_blank">https://www.weau.com/content/misc/Smurfing-how-meth-users-are-taking-advantage-of-over-the-counter-drugs-490238691.html</a>

@Eric Hougland

Urf. That's more than I want to know.
Would that be meth-od acting?

@Linda Jo

"Just smurfing the web."

Underrated comment.

@Super8ing

Sorry to hear your librarians were such pests.  Most I've seen leave everybody alone unless approached.  Having a librarian who acts like a commissioned electronics salesperson has got to be a nightmare.

Anyway, I thought this particular clue fit perfectly.

@Lewis

I thought of both, and, as often advised here, waited for the crosses.
As MOL noted NEIN was a gimme (for me), and the issue was resolved.

@HEK

I could picture Michelangelo’s fresco in my mind, but remembered it as THE CREATION OF Man. I’m lucky that didn’t fit (and that I immediately remembered the correct title). 

Glad you figured out quickly that the perfectly cromulent avid reader was wrong. I’ve found that having a wrong answer in the grid can really slow me down because I can’t see anything that goes through or around it.

@John Carson

Thanks! I hadn’t noticed that.

New York Times: Why hide those options?

@Barry Ancona

Such innocent times when we had the brain space to be worried about the invasion of KILLER BEES.
And then the courage to laugh about it.

@Kevin

That apple fell so far from the tree that it's in a different orchard, and it's rotting on the ground.  

And it's full of worms.

@sonnel

I was in the second grade when RFK was killed. Because it happened late in the evening in LA, the news wasn’t in the next morning’s Burlington [Vermont] Free Press. 

I have a vivid memory of getting to school the next morning to see a bunch of people gathered around the flagpole, including my teacher from the year before, who was sobbing uncontrollably.

@Asky

Mood







No clue if I used that right, I just remember there being some newfangled lingo clue for that over the last year that made zero sense

@Ragland

That sounds exactly like the SWINGSET I grew up with. By the time I was old enough to use it without supervision, it had spent several winters outside in upstate New York and was nice and rusty, too. 

And those swings they have now for infants, with the safety bars? Nowhere in sight.

@Bob T.

My husband is nuts about ocean liners. He and I crossed from Southampton to NYC on the Queen Mary 2 in 2004. It was a fantastic experience, but one that neither of us feels the need to repeat. 

But crosswords for six days? Kinda tempting!

@Barry Ancona
thx for the link.
@Eric
We take a fair number of cruises. We just sailed r/t Brooklyn-Greenland. I lost my streak but it was worth it. ;)

@Bob T.

I recently made the trek from my couch to the fridge to get another beer.

I lost my streak but it was worth it.

@jake

Why should we ignore it? 

It’s been part of the language for over 80 years.

@Darren, oh my! The puzzle is dreadful because there were things you didn't know? 

If you know everything and never have to struggle with a puzzle, why even do them? 

I loved this puzzle. I didn't have any lookups but did need to use crosses to finish. I was 6+ minutes under my Friday average.

@Barry Ancona

Many solvers don't have the kind of memory to recall at that level, especially if they don't solve every day. Look at the dates. Five months to three years between appearances. It doesn't make much sense to bonk them over the head with xwordinfo data. 

Don't feel bad, Darren.

@Mean Old Lady

The guy who I mourned too many years after his actual death.  

The more I read about him, the more I missed him.  I think he would have eclipsed his brother.  He was the last Democrat that seemingly truly believed in empowering the disenfranchised of late 1960's society.

@Lsm

